# JavaScript DOM – Introduction & Selecting Elements

---

## 📘 What is the DOM?

The **Document Object Model (DOM)** is a programming interface that represents an HTML page as a **tree of objects**. JavaScript uses the DOM to read, change, add, or delete HTML elements dynamically.

```
document
└── html
    ├── head
    │   └── title
    └── body
        ├── h1
        ├── p
        └── div
            ├── span
            └── button
```

- **`window`** — the global object (browser window)
- **`document`** — the entry point to the DOM tree
- Every HTML tag becomes a **Node** in the tree

---

## 🔍 Selecting Elements

### By ID
```js
const heading = document.getElementById("main-title");
// Returns: single element or null
```

### By Class Name
```js
const cards = document.getElementsByClassName("card");
// Returns: HTMLCollection (live, array-like — NOT a real array)
```

### By Tag Name
```js
const paragraphs = document.getElementsByTagName("p");
// Returns: HTMLCollection
```

### querySelector (CSS selector — returns FIRST match)
```js
document.querySelector("#main-title");      // by id
document.querySelector(".card");            // by class
document.querySelector("p");               // by tag
document.querySelector("ul li:first-child"); // complex selector
document.querySelector("[data-id='3']");    // attribute selector
// Returns: single element or null
```

### querySelectorAll (returns ALL matches)
```js
const allCards = document.querySelectorAll(".card");
// Returns: NodeList (static snapshot — can use forEach)

allCards.forEach(card => console.log(card));
```

