## 📝 Interview Questions

**Q1. What is the DOM?**
> The Document Object Model is a tree-structured representation of an HTML page created by the browser. It allows JavaScript to access and manipulate every element, attribute, and piece of text on the page as an object.

**Q2. What is the difference between `getElementById` and `querySelector`?**
> `getElementById` selects only by ID and is slightly faster. `querySelector` accepts any valid CSS selector making it far more flexible. Both return a single element (or null).

**Q3. What is the difference between `querySelector` and `querySelectorAll`?**
> `querySelector` returns the **first** matching element. `querySelectorAll` returns a **NodeList** of all matching elements.

**Q4. What is the difference between an HTMLCollection and a NodeList?**
> An HTMLCollection (from `getElementsBy*`) is live — it updates automatically when the DOM changes. A NodeList (from `querySelectorAll`) is a static snapshot. NodeList supports `forEach`; HTMLCollection doesn't.

**Q5. What does `element.closest()` do?**
> It traverses up the DOM tree and returns the nearest ancestor (including itself) that matches the given CSS selector. Useful for event delegation — finding which parent a clicked element belongs to.

**Q6. What is the difference between `children` and `childNodes`?**
> `children` returns only **element nodes** (HTML tags). `childNodes` returns all nodes including text nodes (whitespace, line breaks) and comment nodes.

**Q7. What is `window` vs `document`?**
> `window` is the global browser object — it represents the tab/window and contains methods like `alert()`, `setTimeout()`, `localStorage`. `document` is a property of `window` representing the HTML document tree.

